  <text y="-3415.54" class="text-1" transform="translate(1.75 -6)">
    <tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>The Document Object Model (DOM) allows you to access elements of a web page and enable interaction with </tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>the page by adding and removing elements, changing the order, content and attributes of elements, and even </tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>altering how they are styled.</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>In this chapter, weâ€™ll cover the following topics:</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan> â€¢ Introduction to the DOM</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan> â€¢ Getting elements â€• </tspan><tspan class="code-inline">getElementById</tspan><tspan> , </tspan><tspan class="code-inline">getElementsByClassName</tspan><tspan> , </tspan><tspan class="code-inline">getElementsByTagName</tspan><tspan> , </tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan> </tspan><tspan class="code-inline">querySelector</tspan><tspan> and </tspan><tspan class="code-inline">querySelectorAll</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan> â€¢ Navigating the DOM</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan> â€¢ Getting and setting an elementâ€™s attributes</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan> â€¢ Updating the DOM by creating dynamic markup</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan> â€¢ Changing the CSS of an element</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan> â€¢ Our project â€• we&apos;ll dynamically insert each question into the HTML</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-288.82" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan>
  </text>
  <text x="147.07" y="-1825.96" style="white-space:pre;fill:#333;font-family:&quot;Roboto Slab&quot;;font-size:28px">
    
  </text>
  <text style="font-family:Roboto;font-size:32px;font-weight:300;letter-spacing:.5px;white-space:pre" transform="translate(1504.23 -102.27)">
    <tspan x="-1790.8" y="-1757.01">The Document Object Model, or DOM for short, represents an HTML document as a network of connected </tspan><tspan x="-1790.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>nodes that form a tree-like structure.</tspan><tspan x="-1790.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-1790.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>The DOM treats everything on a web page as a node. HTML tags, the text inside these tags, even the attributes </tspan><tspan x="-1790.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>of a tag are all nodes. The HTML tag is the root node, and every other part of the document is a child node of</tspan><tspan x="-1790.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan> this.</tspan><tspan x="-1790.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-1790.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>Take the following piece of HTML as an example:</tspan>
  </text>
