    <tspan x="-259.55" y="-1296.35" style="fill:#8596bb">&lt;</tspan><tspan>p </tspan><tspan style="fill:#408fb5">class</tspan><tspan>=</tspan><tspan style="fill:#709b1f">&apos;warning&apos;</tspan><tspan style="fill:#47629d">&gt;</tspan><tspan>Something has gone </tspan><tspan style="fill:#677dad">&lt;</tspan><tspan>em</tspan><tspan style="fill:#6379aa">&gt;</tspan><tspan>very</tspan><tspan style="fill:#47629d">&lt;/</tspan><tspan>em</tspan><tspan style="fill:#47629d">&gt;</tspan><tspan> wrong!</tspan><tspan style="fill:#46629d">&lt;/</tspan><tspan>p</tspan><tspan style="fill:#405c9a">&gt;</tspan>
  </text>
  <text x="-283.31" y="-164.28" style="fill:#333;font-family:Roboto;font-size:32px;letter-spacing:.5px;white-space:pre">The DOM tree
  </text>
  <text x="-265.78" y="-26.67" class="text-1" transform="translate(-20.8 -15.75)">The DOM is not actually part of JavaScript because it islanguage agnostic(although JavaScript is, by far, the <tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan>language most commonly used with it). This means it can be used in any programming language, not just <tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan>JavaScript. We can use JavaScript to access and modify different parts of a web page using a special built-in <tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan>object called document.
  </text>
  <text style="fill:#333;font-family:Roboto;font-size:73px;letter-spacing:-2.5px;white-space:pre" transform="translate(-177.02 4114.02)">
    <tspan x="-109.55" y="-3801.36">History of the DOM</tspan><tspan x="-109.55" dy="1em">â€‹</tspan>
  </text>
  <text class="text-1" transform="translate(-20.8 472.3)">
    <tspan x="-265.78" y="-26.67">In the early days of the web, browser vendors such as Netscape and Microsoft developed their own distinct </tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>ways of accessing and altering parts of a web page. In the beginning, they tended to focus on common page </tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>elements such as images, links and forms â€“ this was known as Dynamic HTML (DHTML). These methods </tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>became known as DOM level 0, or legacy DOM. Some of the more common methods, such as those used for </tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>selecting images and forms, can still be used in the current DOM.</tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) started to standardize the process, and created the DOM level 1 in</tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>1998. This introduced a complete model for web pages that allowed every part of them to be navigated.</tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>The DOM level 2 specification was published in 2000 and introduced the popular </tspan><tspan class="code-inline">getElementById()</tspan><tspan> method, </tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>which made it much easier to access specific elements on a web page. The DOM level 3 specification was </tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>published in 2004, and since then the W3C has abandoned using levels. The DOM specification is developed </tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>as a </tspan><tspan style="text-decoration:underline solid rgba(255,255,255,.8)">living standard</tspan><tspan>.</tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>Despite the standardization process, browsers have not always implemented the DOM consistently, so itâ€™s </tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>been difficult to program for in the past. Fortunately, since Internet Explorer 8, DOM support has been much </tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>more consistent, and modern browsers now implement the current DOM level 3. Theyâ€™re also implementing </tspan><tspan x="-265.78" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>more of the new DOM level 4 features with every update.</tspan>
  </text>
  <text style="fill:#333;font-family:Roboto;font-size:49px;letter-spacing:-2.5px;white-space:pre" transform="translate(-173.6 5457.5)">
    <tspan x="-109.55" y="-3801.36">An Example Web Page</tspan><tspan x="-109.55" dy="1em">â€‹</tspan>
  </text>
  
