    <text style="white-space:pre" x="166.1" y="3701.1" fill="#333" font-family="Roboto" font-size="32" letter-spacing=".5">The DOM tree
    </text>
    <text style="white-space:pre" x="-265.8" y="-26.7" transform="translate(434.5 3831)" fill="#333" font-family="Roboto" font-size="32" font-weight="300" letter-spacing=".5">The DOM is not actually part of JavaScript because it islanguage agnostic(although JavaScript is, by far, the <tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan>language most commonly used with it). This means it can be used in any programming language, not just <tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan>JavaScript. We can use JavaScript to access and modify different parts of a web page using a special built-in <tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan>object called document.
    </text>
    <text transform="translate(278.2 7960.8)" style="white-space:pre" fill="#333" font-family="Roboto" font-size="73" letter-spacing="-2.5">
      <tspan x="-109.5" y="-3801.4">History of the DOM</tspan><tspan x="-109.5" dy="1em">â€‹</tspan>
    </text>
    <text transform="translate(434.5 4319.1)" style="white-space:pre" fill="#333" font-family="Roboto" font-size="32" font-weight="300" letter-spacing=".5">
      <tspan x="-265.8" y="-26.7">In the early days of the web, browser vendors such as Netscape and Microsoft developed their own distinct </tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>ways of accessing and altering parts of a web page. In the beginning, they tended to focus on common page </tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>elements such as images, links and forms â€“ this was known as Dynamic HTML (DHTML). These methods </tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>became known as DOM level 0, or legacy DOM. Some of the more common methods, such as those used for </tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>selecting images and forms, can still be used in the current DOM.</tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) started to standardize the process, and created the DOM level 1 in</tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>1998. This introduced a complete model for web pages that allowed every part of them to be navigated.</tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>The DOM level 2 specification was published in 2000 and introduced the popular </tspan><tspan class="mono">getElementById()</tspan><tspan> method, </tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>which made it much easier to access specific elements on a web page. The DOM level 3 specification was </tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>published in 2004, and since then the W3C has abandoned using levels. The DOM specification is developed </tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>as a </tspan><tspan text-decoration="underline solid rgba(255,255,255,.8)">living standard</tspan><tspan>.</tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>Despite the standardization process, browsers have not always implemented the DOM consistently, so itâ€™s </tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>been difficult to program for in the past. Fortunately, since Internet Explorer 8, DOM support has been much </tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>more consistent, and modern browsers now implement the current DOM level 3. Theyâ€™re also implementing </tspan><tspan x="-265.8" dy="1.8em">â€‹</tspan><tspan>more of the new DOM level 4 features with every update.</tspan>
    </text>
    <text transform="translate(281.7 9304.3)" style="white-space:pre" fill="#333" font-family="Roboto" font-size="73" letter-spacing="-2.5">
      <tspan x="-109.5" y="-3801.4">An Example Web Page</tspan><tspan x="-109.5" dy="1em">â€‹</tspan>
